"CORE_NARRATIVE: Real-world light field depth estimation is severely bottlenecked by the unrealistic **single-material assumption** and the prohibitive computational cost of existing models. By introducing a unified framework with **dual masks** and **domain-balanced sampling**, we achieve highly efficient depth estimation across **mixed physical domains** using only **754K parameters**, enabling practical **edge deployment**.\n\nINTRO_HOOK: Open by contrasting the idealized Lambertian assumption of current models with the messy reality of **mixed physical domains**, immediately highlighting how this **single-material assumption** causes severe performance degradation and hinders practical **edge deployment**.\n\nGAP_BRIDGE: Transition by emphasizing that while existing methods either overfit to single domains or rely on heavy architectures, there is a critical lack of lightweight baselines capable of handling diverse reflections, thus necessitating a unified approach driven by **domain-balanced sampling** and strict parameter constraints.\n\nMETHOD_JUSTIFY: Justify the **dual masks** (Medium and Angular Direction) as the explicit mechanism to disentangle complex reflections without bloating the network, and the **754K parameters** multi-directional EPI design as the direct architectural answer to the **edge deployment** constraint.\n\nEXPERIMENT_VALIDATE: Validate the core claim by highlighting the 26% overall MAE reduction and 41% Non-Lambertian error drop, proving that overcoming the **single-material assumption** via **domain-balanced sampling** yields robust accuracy across **mixed physical domains** while strictly maintaining the **754K parameters** limit.\n\nCONCLUSION_ECHO: Conclude by reiterating that breaking the **single-material assumption** with our unified, **754K parameters** framework successfully bridges the gap between complex **mixed physical domains** and real-world **edge deployment**, establishing a highly efficient new baseline for 3D perception."